<DOCNO> AP900604-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
colombias chief of police said monday 
his country cannot fight drug traffickers alone and called on 
western nations to increase its efforts to combat trafficking 
police chief gen miguel gomez padilla said in an interview that 
industrialized countries must fight drugs on all levels from ending 
arms sales to drug traffickers to tightening banking laws to stop 
drug barons from laundering their money 
to end narcotrafficking what is required is an atttack on all 
levels of the process including consumption gomez told the ap 
we need cooperation from the rest of the world to end drug 
trafficking 
he made his comments as colombian president virgilio barco was 
visiting washington to discuss the drug war with president bush 
gomez said western countries are cooperating in the drug war but 
he said the aid will never be enough 
colombia has insisted that drug trafficking is a multinational 
crime he said 
he added it is indispensible that there be strong action on 
the part of industrialized countries to attack consumption 
colombia supplies an estimated 80 percent of all the cocaine 
consumed in the united states 
maj jorge humberto martin press spokesman for the national 
police said colombia needs communications and transportation 
equipment more helicopters and more money to fight drug barons 
colombia launched a crackdown of drug traffickers early this year 
that gomez said has succeeded in reducing cocaine exports by 20 to 
30 percent 
in response the powerful medellin cocaine cartel has carried out 
a campaign of bombings and assassinations that has left an average 
of two policemen dead each day this year 
bush met in february with the presidents of colombia bolivia and 
peru and promised the united states would increase its aid in the 
fight against drug traffickers 
gomez said bush has increased us aid but said not enough 
controls have been put on the laundering of drug money 
we have insisted on the control of laundering capital and this 
has been happening but not to the degree that we would have 
liked gomez said 
on may 27 cesar gaviria of the ruling liberal party was elected 
to succeed barco of the major presidential candidates gaviria took 
the hardest line against drug traffickers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

