<TEXT>
a tentative settlement was 
announced monday in a british columbia truckers strike that has 
disrupted commercial traffic at us border crossings 
but some strikers denounced it and pledged to keep their border 
blockades in place 
about two dozen us truckers who had delivered their loads in 
canada and were then stranded at the border were allowed to head 
home monday night through the blaine wash border crossing but 
most loaded trucks remained blocked there 
passenger cars buses and trucks carrying medical supplies mail 
and fresh produce were allowed through 
bryan williams the provincial governments chief mediator in the 
strike said agreements had been signed between the independent 
truckers and a fairly substantial number of employers 
the blockades have resulted in food and fuel shortages in the 
province and in point roberts a small peninsula thats part of 
washington state but reachable only through british columbia or by 
water 
the president of the western owner operators association don 
tofsrud said the independent truckers were being asked to dismantle 
their blockades 
im asking all the guys to get home and get some sleep 
tofsrud said 
but several hours later the blockade continued at blaine 
details of the tentative settlement were withheld but some 
striking truckers reacted negatively to reports theyd heard 
doug neal a spokesman for striking truckers at the blaine 
crossing said a pay demand of 40 per hour in canadian currency 
34 us was nonnegotiable 
if we dont get it were going to stay here until we do he 
said 
the truckers pay their own operating costs they presently are 
paid 26 to 35 an hour canadian about 22 and 29 us 
more than 1000 independent british columbia truckers have 
participated in a series of escalating job actions since withdrawing 
their services a week ago to obtain higher hauling rates the 
blockade of four border points between british columbia and 
washington state and along two major canadian highways began in 
earnest friday 
idled drivers at the washington state border city of blaine at 
the end of interstate 5 said monday they were growing angry and 
wanted to go home 
we got trapped up here said dick tallmadge of kent wash 
who estimated he was losing about 100 us a day in mileage 
payments 
tallmadge said he didnt understand how keeping us drivers 
hostage aided the canadian truckers 
were not doing them any good he said we are a thorn in 
their side 
were tow truckers of war said dyke stewart of raleigh 
nc 
stewart later announced the agreement that let empty us trucks 
return home through blaine he said american truckers who refused to 
let their trailers be examined to show they were empty or who were 
carrying goods back to the united states would not be allowed to 
move 
</TEXT>
