<TEXT>
horst marggraf scanned the meat section of an 
east berlin grocery store and dropped a brightly labeled package of 
west german ham into his shopping cart 
i dont normally buy west german meat but i have relatives 
coming said marggraf 61 
a month before the historic economic union of the germanys east 
german consumers already are setting the stage for massive 
unemployment with their preference for western goods 
hundreds of thousands of workers are expected to lose their jobs 
as the centrally planned economy is dismantled and individual 
sectors are forced to compete with western enterprises honed by the 
laws of supply and demand 
east german makers of electronics clothing and household goods 
have cut prices up to 90 percent in a desperate attempt to compete 
with western products that are considered far superior 
nowhere are the effects of competition more evident than in 
grocery stores where a flood of western meat potatoes soups and 
sausages is eroding the vast collective farm system that typifies 
communism 
experts are conducting experiments as one of historys quickest 
economic transitions takes place 
we put east german yogurt in west german packaging put it in 
some stores and people bought it at a 31 rate to east 
germanpackaged yogurt said andries kurjo agriculture analyst 
for the institute for intergerman economic and social affairs in 
west berlin 
consumers were willing to pay three times as much and swore it 
tasted better he said 
kurjo who spent 10 years analyzing east german agriculture for 
the us embassy in east berlin said 20 percent to 30 percent of 
the east german food industry had been lost to west german firms in 
recent months 
he estimated only onethird of the 3800 collective farms could 
make it without government subsidies 
only the best those with the most flexible leaders have the 
possibility to survive kurjo said 
food began pouring in from the west in march when the two east 
german government agencies involved signed contracts with western 
distributors 
about twothirds of the east berlin stores now sell western meat 
vegetables fruit juice and milk 
the sudden competition in what was a captive market has made 
farmers perhaps the most rebellious segment of the work force 
thousands have blocked border crossings with their antiquated 
tractors they have rallied in major cities to demand limits on 
imports and government help for their collectives 
nearly 900000 east germans about 10 percent of the work force 
earn their livelihoods in agriculture 
east germany is to become a free market formally on july 2 when 
its economy and social institutions are essentially absorbed by west 
germany in the most significant phase of german unification 
kurjo said agriculture makes up about 10 percent of the economy 
and about 40 percent of the average east germans paycheck is spent 
on food 
western competition has led to a huge oversupply of domestic 
agricultural products he said there have been reports of farmers 
destroying crops and animals because of shrinking demand 
at a farm near merseburg in the south hubert hempel 42 said 
the operation was plagued by oversupply 
we must slaughter small pigs because we cannot sell them and 
cannot afford to feed them he said 
under the old system prices paid to farmers were artificially 
high and those charged consumers were artificially low the subsidy 
amounted to 32 billion marks 9 billion a year about 12 percent 
of east germanys budget 
collectives operated on the basis of guaranteed prices for their 
products and guaranteed salaries for their workers 
farmers now find distributors will not buy at the artificially 
high prices and even with lower domestic prices consumers still 
favor western products 
customers bought attractively packaged west german sausage for 
399 east german marks in an east berlin grocery store even though 
a larger quantity of east german sausage cost only 79 pfennigs 
about onefifth as much 
west german yogurt in a glossy plastic container adorned with 
pictures of fruit sells for 255 marks or 76 cents east german 
yogurt in a glass bottle with an illfitting lid costs 38 pfennigs 
11 cents 
like most east german enterprises the collective farms employ 
too many people for the amount of work to be done kurjo said the 
average for a 6000acre farm was about 350 workers 
they had a curious system of keeping as many people on their 
farms as possible because the income paid by the government was 
based on how many employees a collective had he said 
harry nebelung a 51yearold agricultural engineer in charge of 
vegetable production on a collective in saarmund about 30 miles 
south of berlin said his operation could thrive but only if it 
changed 
we have too many people he said if we had larger 
tractors we wouldnt need them 
kurjo said he was astonished to learn that most east german 
farmers wanted to keep their collectives intact rather than become 
owners of private farms 
unlike western farms whose owners often work seven days a week 
the collectives are run more like factories employees have a 
43hour week with guaranteed holidays and sick days 
they have been educated as specialists a feed mixer a 
milker kurjo said they know nothing of the economy which a 
western farmer must be expert in 
</TEXT>
