<TEXT>
overcrowding in the nations jails is steadily 
worsening and part of the problem is that jails are holding inmates 
for overfilled state prisons according to the justice department 
on june 30 1989 there were 395553 prisoners held in jails 
operated by local governments designed to hold 367769 people 
according to a study released sunday by the departments bureau of 
justice statistics 
that marked a 15 percent increase from the 343569 prisoners in 
custody on the same day in 1988 when the jails had a rated capacity 
of 339633 
meanwhile the capacity of local jails expanded 8 percent between 
the middle of 1988 and midyear 1989 the study said 
the average daily population of the nations local jails for the 
12 months ending june 30 1989 was 386845 also up 15 percent from 
an average of 336017 for the same 12month period ending june 30 
1988 the study said 
the occupancy rate of the nations jails increased from 101 
percent to 108 percent between the two periods the study said in 
1983 the occupancy rate of nations jails was 85 percent and in 
1976 it was 65 percent 
overcrowding was worse in the jurisdictions that had the largest 
number of inmates the occupancy rate averaged 116 percent in the 
508 local jurisdictions that held at least 100 inmates these 
jurisdictions had 81 percent of the nations jail prisoners 
state prison overcrowding also contributed to the problem in 
local jails according to the study the study found that 88 percent 
of the 508 largest jurisdictions held 42053 prisoners for other 
authorities including 29358 inmates that had been sent to local 
jails because of overcrowding elsewhere the study said 
twentysix percent of these jurisdictions were under a court 
order to reduce overcrowding at one or more jails and 23 percent had 
been ordered by judges to improve conditions 
despite the increased overcrowding the number of inmate deaths 
declined from 469 during 1988 to 414 last year the study said the 
number of jail suicides declined from 147 to 121 
there were 19 million admissions and releases from local jails 
during the 12month period ending june 30 1989 
the average daily population of female jail inmates jumped 27 
percent between 1988 and 1989 women comprised 9 percent of all jail 
inmates in 1989 the study said 
the study surveyed local jails that hold inmates after 
arraignment usually more than 48 hours 
police lockups that house prisoners usually drunks for less 
than 48 hours were not included staterun jails and the combined 
jailprison systems of alaska connecticut delaware hawaii rhode 
island and vermont were not included in the survey 
</TEXT>
