<TEXT>
the yellow ribbon on kit and joan 
sutherlands frontdoor knocker is now frayed and faded but that 
doesnt mean the sisters have given up waiting for their father 
held hostage five years in lebanon 
thomas sutherland a scottishborn american abducted by shiite 
moslem extremists in beirut on june 9 1985 has been described by 
former hostage david jacobsen as one strong tough scottish 
farmer 
and pessimism is not a family trait 
i think because dad is so strong and really a 
happygolucky wild ornery kind of person that its really 
difficult not to be that way kit sutherland said 
and so sometimes you reach the frustrations but we learned 
from the very beginning not to get on the roller coaster to watch 
what happens and wait until you see things 
but joan said i really think somethings going to happen 
maybe not tomorrow but maybe by the end of the summer 
kit 29 and joan 25 share a house in this university town at 
the foot of the rocky mountains sutherlands other child ann 31 
lives with her husband and daughter in california 
sutherland 59 was the dean of agriculture and food science at 
the american university of beirut and was on leave from colorado 
state university in fort collins when gunmen kidnapped him as he 
drove in a convoy to beirut airport 
his family stays hopeful by looking at the small things the 
fact that some of them have died and dad hasnt kit said 
a lot of things have happened that they the hostages could 
have been killed for she said so you have to stay optimistic 
that at least the most rational of groups the most rational of 
terrorists has him 
sutherland traveled from scotland to the united states in the 
1950s to continue his agriculture studies at iowa state university 
he met his wife jean there and married 
he became a us citizen in 1963 but retained his love for his 
native land 
he knows robert burns poems recalled freed hostage rev 
lawrence martin jenco who shared a years captivity with 
sutherland and he would recite them with that wonderful scots 
accent 
his daughters also credit the strength of their mother jean 
with keeping their hopes high 
mrs sutherland 56 teaches english at american university and 
except for visits to see her daughters has remained in beirut she 
was in fort collins finishing her doctoral thesis when her husband 
was kidnapped 
kit sutherland an animalsciences research assistant at csu and 
joan who works at a fort collins lending company say the last five 
years have not exactly been on hold 
but they have learned what it means to be hostage daughters 
its gone fast in some ways because you realize that life goes 
really fast and in that sense hes missed a lot kit said but 
in the other sense it just seems to drag by because you want him to 
finally get out its only been every once in a while that its 
difficult to keep optimistic 
the release of two american hostages in april and a recent 
report in a beirut magazine saying sutherland was ill and would be 
released soon are encouraging signs she said 
dad has never been the one to be the next one she said 
weve never thought he was the one that was coming out so this is 
the first time that weve had any indication that he might be 
freed 
the sisters plan to mark the fifth anniversary of his captivity 
at events in the fort collins and denver areas they admitted that 
anniversary dates can be stressful but said the university 
community and fort collins residents have been very supportive 
throughout fort collins yellow ribbons flutter from trees 
houses offices schools and churches 
those ribbons routinely are replaced with new ones but the 
ribbon tied on the sutherlands door is weatherbeaten 
were not taking it down until hes released joan said 
