<TEXT>
robert noyce an inventor of the computer 
chip that revolutionized electronics and helped usher in the 
information age has died of a heart attack at 62 
the computer pioneer died sunday at seton medical center 
working separately in the late 1950s noyce and jack s kilby 
invented the integrated circuit which made possible rapid gains in 
computer technology by putting the power of multiple transistors on 
a single tiny chip 
computer chips or semiconductors are used in everything from 
personal computers and pocket calculators to microwaves and medical 
equipment 
very few things have changed the world as dramatically as the 
integrated circuit said robert m white president of the 
national academy of engineering the development of the integrated 
circuit was the single most important event that helped to usher in 
the information age 
noyce was a founder in 1968 of intel corp the nations 
thirdlargest semiconductor producer 
in 1988 he was appointed chief executive and president of 
sematech the governmentindustry group set up to help the united 
states recover world leadership in semiconductor manufacturing from 
the japanese 
noyce was a legend within the electronics industry spokesman 
jim jarrett said from intels santa clara calif headquarters 
bob was an instrumental figure in creating what has become a 
50 billion industry and semiconductors are the driving force 
behind a 500 billion electronics industry said stan victor 
spokesman for texas instruments inc 
noyce once said american leadership in semiconductor 
manufacturing is essential to the nations economic and military 
security he said us companies must adopt the cooperative 
practices of their japanese competitors to regain it 
noyce was born in burlington iowa he earned bachelors degrees 
from grinnell college in grinnell iowa in physics and mathematics 
noyce earned a phd in physics from the massachusetts institute of 
technology in 1953 
he became a researcher at philco corp then moved to the 
shockley semiconductor laboratory he cofounded fairchild 
semiconductor corp in 1957 
he was working at fairchild and kilby at texas instruments when 
they invented the integrated circuit 
noyce was inducted into the national inventors hall of fame in 
1983 
survivors include his wife ann bowers four children and 12 
grandchildren 
funeral plans were incomplete 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

