<TEXT>
jewelry guns and guitars are the most common 
wares look around stanton myersons pawnshop and youll also find 
a telescope a diabetes monitor and a television marked prison 
approved 
a steady stream of visitors moved through the store on a recent 
weekday afternoon in this economically depressed city near 
philadelphia some were seeking loans some were buying goods left 
as collateral and never reclaimed 
basically its bluecollar people who live from paycheck to 
paycheck who need at times extra funds to carry them over to the 
next paycheck said myerson owner of lous loan inc in chester 
and upper darby 
although widely overlooked by policymakers and researchers 
pawnshops are an important but costly source of credit to the poor 
according to a recent study by swarthmore college economics 
professor john p caskey and student brian j zikmund 
millions of americans borrow about 50 at a time typically 
reclaiming their goods in two to three months the study found they 
pay interest and fees ranging from an annual 36 percent in 
pennsylvania and new jersey to 240 percent in oklahoma 
most pawnshop customers come from lowincome economic groups 
and are probably ineligible for bank or finance company credit 
caskey and zikmund write in the federal reserve bank of kansas 
citys economic review journal 
pawnshops are on the rise in response to bank deregulation 
falling real wages for production workers and a growing poverty 
rate the researchers say they deal in smaller amounts than 
traditional lenders like to handle and are seeking enhanced 
respectability in suburban shopping centers 
most pawnbrokers own perhaps two or three shops cash america 
investments a fort worth texasbased company with 100 pawnshops in 
three states is traded on the american stock exchange 
policymakers obviously dont think a lot about pawnshops 
caskey said in an interview theres a great deal of attention to 
banks and now of course savings and loans but theres a 
phenomenon growing here that people arent aware of i think they 
ought to be paying some attention to it 
an estimated 6900 pawnshops provided about 689 million in loans 
in 1988 the study said the amount was less than 01 percent of the 
nations 744 billion outstanding consumer credit that year 
but at an average of 50 each some 35 million loans were spread 
among as much as 10 percent of the nations adults allowing for 
multiple loans to some customers 
during the 1980s the pawnbroking industry grew in almost all 
states for which data could be obtained the researchers say 
there is a movement now among pawnbrokers to try to clean up 
their image caskey said theyre trying to move out to the 
suburbs provide welllit very clean professionally managed 
stores with squeaky clean images 
he said he found little evidence to back up the popular 
perception that pawnshops are fronts for stolen goods obviously 
it happens but its very rare he said 
pawnshops must register pawned goods and the names of individuals 
pawning them with police authorities can seize stolen items 
costing the brokers both their collateral and the loaned money 
in oklahoma just 015 percent of pawned goods were confiscated 
by police as stolen property the study said 
state and local governments regulate how much pawnshops can 
charge for interest storage and insurance in more than half the 
states pawnshops can levy an effective 120 percent interest rate or 
more on the averagesized loan the researchers say 
state and local laws also determine what can be pawned in 
delaware false teeth and artificial limbs are offlimits 
pennsylvania pawnshops must see proof of ownership before accepting 
workers tools 
 
</TEXT>
