<TEXT>
fellow actors mourned sir rex harrison as a 
master of high comedy who played the crotchety elocutionist in my 
fair lady and talked with the animals as the lovable dr dolittle 
during a 66year career 
the tony and oscarwinning actor remembered for his wit and 
charm as well as his versatility and skill on the stage and screen 
died in his sleep early saturday at his manhattan home he was 82 
harrison had been ill only a short time and did not know he had 
pancreatic cancer said his attorney harold schiff his doctors had 
told him he was suffering from gallbladder trouble 
he didnt want to know schiff said 
harrison debuted on broadway in 1936 and last performed there on 
may 11 as lord porteous in the revival of the circle w 
somerset maughams 1920s comedy 
he died with his boots on no question about it said elliot 
martin producer of the circle and three other harrison shows 
harrison became inexorably linked with the henry higgins 
character in my fair lady winning a tony award in 1957 for his 
broadway run with julie andrews and an academy award in 1964 for his 
screen version opposite audrey hepburn 
to watch him and to work with him was a joyful experience i 
doubt there was anyone before like him andrews said the 
