the supreme court agreed today to decide 
whether passengers on international flights may sue airlines for 
emotional distress allegedly suffered in nearcrashes that cause 
them no physical harm 
the court said it will review a ruling that eastern airlines may 
be forced to pay passengers on a flight that landed safely in miami 
after all the planes engines failed briefly in the air 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals ruled last year that the 
socalled wa an international air travel treaty 
permits airlines to be sued in such cases rsaw conventionby passengers 
who suffer 
only psychological trauma 
an airline is required by the treaty to pay up to 75000 per 
person depending on the severity of injuries the liability ceiling 
is lifted only if the airline is shown to have committed willful 
misconduct 
the treaty only covers international flights in domestic 
flights the law of the state in which a lawsuit was filed would 
apply lawyers for eastern airlines said in most states passengers 
on domestic flights who can prove negligence but not willful 
misconduct would be barred from recovering damages for emotional 
distress unaccompanied by physical injury 
the 11th circuit court ruled in the case of eastern flight 855 
which left miami on may 5est in hong kong 
where about 100000 demonstrated hong kong reverts to chinese rule 
in 1997 
smaller demonstrations were held in taiwan japan britain 
canada and the united states 
