<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear a bush 
administration appeal aimed at giving federal officials more power 
to deny temporary legal status to immigrant farmworkers 
the court without comment said it will review a ruling that 
said the workers are entitled to various procedural protections when 
applying for such residential permits 
the case stems from a 1988 lawsuit by the haitian refugee center 
the migration and refugee services of the roman catholic diocese of 
palm beach fla and 17 applicants for temporary residence the 
classaction suit is intended to benefit thousands of aliens 
the suit said applicants for temporary residency were being 
denied their rights under a 1986 federal law that established a 
program for admitting foreign farmworkers to the united states 
to be eligible for the program aliens must have applied during 
an 18month period that ended nov 30 1988 and have done migrant 
farm work for at least 90 days during a oneyear period that ended 
may 1 1986 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals last year upheld a federal 
judges ruling that required the immigration and naturalization 
service ins to take a number of steps to assure applicants are 
treated fairly when interviewed for temporary residency 
thosnslators permitting applicants to present witnesses and 
requiring ins interviewers to explain what evidence they relied on 
in ruling on applications 
the appeals court said the 1986 immigration law granted aliens 
a constitutionally protected right to apply for temporary residency 
as well as a right to substantiate their claims for eligibility 
once congress chooses to create such a system of entitlements a 
property interest is created that is accorded procedural due process 
protection 
bush administration lawyers in the appeal acted on today said 
the law does not give federal judges such sweeping authority 
the 11th circuit court ruling has sanctioned the improper 
intervention of federal district courts into the daytoday business 
of administering the immigration laws the government lawyers said 
the appeal said ins has received more than 13 million 
applications under the 1986 law for temporary residency and approved 
93 percent of them but the appeal said tens of thousands of 
applications for temporary permits could be affected by the appeals 
court ruling 
the appeal added that the 11th circuit courts ruling could have 
a bearing on additional thousands of applications for permanent 
residential status under the 1986 law 
the case is mcnary vs haitian refugee center 891332 
</TEXT>
