law 
by a 54 vote the justices said illinois officials improperly 
censured an attorney who said on his professional letterhead he is a 
civil trial specialist certified by the national board of trial 
advocacy nbta a private organization 
justice john paul stevens in the courts main opinion said 
states may not ban potentially misleading information if the 
information also may be presented in a way that is not deceptive 
he was joined by justices william j brennan harry a blackmun 
and anthony m kennedy 
justice thurgood marshall provided the fifth vote to overturn the 
censure of gary e peel of edwardsville ill 
but marshall said states could take steps short of an outright 
ban to assure that lawyer advertising is not misleading 
marshall said peel could be required for example to say on his 
letterhead that the nbta is a private group 
dissenting were chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
sandra day oconnor byron r white and antonin scalia 
the illinois supreme court which disciplines that states 
lawyers had upheld a state rule against advertising oneself as a 
certified civil trial specialist 
the state court censured peel who since 1983 included the 
specialist reference on his letterhead 
the state court said peels use of the reference is misleading 
because it makes it appear he is more qualified than other lawyers 
who do the same type of work 
stevens said today the facts stated on peels letterhead are 
true and verifiable we are satisfied that the consuming public 
understands that a host of certificates are issued by 
private organizations it seems unlikely that peels statement 
about his certification as a specialist by an identified national 
organization necessarily would be confused with formal state 
recognition 
in illinois only lawyers who specialize in patent trademark and 
admiralty law have been allowed to advertise their specialities 
the illinois supreme court said the reason for allowing those 
exceptions was to help the public find attorneys who practice those 
unusual specialities 
the nbta based in boston said it uses rigorous standards to 
determine whether any civil or criminal trial advocate is entitled 
to its certification 
it said it has certified more than 1000 lawyers nationwide 
the supreme court in 1977 struck down a ban on all lawyer 
advertising ruling that it violated freespeech rights since then 
the court has upheld some regulation of lawyer ads but struck down 
other rules 
the case is peel vs attorney registration and disciplinary 
commission of illinois 881775 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

