<TEXT>
justice delayed is not always justice 
denied the vermont supreme court said today as it upheld a 
sixmonth moratorium on civil jury trials in the state 
the moratorium was imposed by the court in january as a way to 
cope with budget cuts prompted by the states sagging economy in 
todays decision the states highest court said constitutional 
guarantees to speedy trials do not mean instant ones 
in its ruling the court noted that the moratorium is temporary 
and it provides for exceptions where justice requires 
the supreme court imposed the ban after it was ordered to cut 
about 300000 from its current year budget to help avert a state 
deficit 
the ban affected only civil cases such things as divorces 
property disputes personal injury claims malpractice suits and 
breaches of contract it did not affect criminal matters and will 
expire july 1 
the 220member vermont trial lawyers association filed a 
classaction lawsuit on behalf of 18 vermonters seeking to overturn 
the ban the associations suit claimed that both the federal and 
state constitutions guarantee vermonters the right to a speedy trial 
it violates the constitutional rights of everyone who has asked 
for a civil jury trial in the state of vermont association 
president jerome oneill said you cant simply decide that youre 
not going to provide civil jury trials 
but the supreme court decision written by retired chief justice 
albert barney said that caseloads cannot be managed on the 
simplistic position that everyone is entitled to an immediate trial 
whenever they are ready for one 
the vermont supreme court decision is counter to a federal court 
ruling in california that held that civil jury trials in us 
district court could not be suspended because of fiscal restraints 
but the vermont justices said the federal ruling centered around 
the length of the moratorium not the moratorium itself and that 
vermont moratorium delayed civil jury trials for a relatively 
short period of time 
the moratorium on civil jury trials should save about 75000 
said lee suskin director of trial court administration 
