the supreme court today rejected a request by 
an unusual coalition of religious groups that it reconsider its 
decision letting states outlaw the use of illegal drugs as a 
religious practice 
the court as expected turned down the petition for 
rehearing without comment such requests are almost never granted 
groups including the american jewish congress the national 
association of evangelicals the national council of churches the 
presbyterian church usa lutheran church missouri synod american 
friends service committee americans united for separation of church 
and state and the christian legal society had joined in filing the 
request 
the april 17 high court ruling in an oregon case said members of 
the native american church have no constitutional right to take the 
hallucinogenic drug peyote during religious ceremonies 
religious leaders said they were more disturbed by the courts 
method of deciding the case than by the decisions bottom line 
five members of 63 court majority agreed that religious beliefs 
cannot excuse failure to comply with otherwise valid laws 
prohibiting conduct states are free to regulate 
the april decision did not require states to have a compelling 
reason before forcing someone to comply with laws interfering with 
religious beliefs 
the case is employment division vs smith 881213 
