here are excerpts from the speech of soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev to a group of us business 
executives on sunday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a few hours ago president bush and i together at our press 
conference summed up the results of the washington summit i 
personally believe that this summit will go down in history as a 
summit of hope and optimism 
it took us some time a long time and a long road to reach this 
stage in our relationship i dont know sometimes when we express 
big hopes we have to knock on wood anyway let me say that we do 
have high hopes we hope that there will be very important political 
and politicalmilitary consequences of this summit and also very 
positive consequences in all other spheres of relations between our 
countries 
the important question is what kind of soviet union do the 
president and the us people want to see does america want to see 
a soviet union that lacks confidence that is not stable that is in 
turmoil or does america want to see the soviet union as a noble 
democratic state which is moving toward new forms of life within the 
overall framework of humanism and democracy a soviet union that is 
working with the entire global civilization integrated in that 
civilization 
so this is the alternative and basically the same alternative 
confronts us that is to say what kind of us do we want to see i 
have thought about that for a long time 
a world that is not comfortable for the us is not comfortable 
for us 
the president and i spent several hours together the two of us 
during this visit our final discussions were in camp david without 
neckties our sleeves rolled up and we discussed things in a very 
intensive way and i feel that as a result we have a new degree of 
confidence and mutual understanding 
now my second point is about the process of change in our 
economy about perestroika in our economy i would like to be brief 
many of you i think must have visited moscow or i dont know 
maybe quite a few have not 
i listened and talked to members of the economic council in 
moscow and i tried to tell them what we intend to do with our 
economy and how we plan to do it the last five years is a period 
that has not been simple for us 
we had to sort things out to understand what kind of a society we 
have what are the good things that we are able to do and what are 
the misjudgments that we have to abandon we were trying to do that 
in a very thorough way and also in a very tough way toward 
ourselves in a selfcritical way toward ourselves 
and in addition to studying ourselves we were trying also to 
test certain new elements and new forms of economic management 
we tried quite a few things in order to gain experience and tried to 
place our management people and production units into a new 
situation new conditions new circumstances and we have seen that 
the whole process moved ahead with great difficulty 
why because of that command system that we have the command 
system in politics and in the economy our economic managers many 
of them very good people who know how to work were used to a system 
of commands to a system of taking orders from above and that 
really happened for many many years many decades 
and a certain type of individual a certain type of economic 
manager evolved and it is very difficult to abandon those old ways 
particularly for people who are not that young 
but in the same way the command system worked as regards those 
who actually worked the machines who actually drive the tractors 
who work in the research labs all of them too basically are that 
type of individual they of course wanted freedom and economic 
autonomy but once they got that they were afraid 
they didnt know how to use that much freedom so this gives you 
an idea of the scope of the problems and this is how we began 
changing a system means changing people intelligent people its 
not just a system some kind of layout that you see on a piece of 
paper and you can just tear up that piece of paper a system is 
people people who live people who have their own interests who 
have their own lives and we have this conflict of interest and 
really had a problem trying to move these new economic forms ahead 
and we were only able to approach that when we began a political 
reform that involved the masses of the people in the political 
process 
if the economic reform is successful then people will not need 
rallies demonstrations and so on although of course quite a few 
rallies and demonstrations i think are going to happen before we are 
successful in economic reform 
we have made mistakes this is true there has been some damage 
done to our economy we have had some problems in management because 
the old system of running the economy has become weaker and the new 
economic leaders the new economic forms of a market economy have 
not yet evolved properly 
the entire structure of a market economy is only beginning to 
evolve so therefore we need to adopt a number of other laws and 
documents that will make it possible for our economy to really work 
among market principles so i think that we are now at this 
watershed when we are ready to move resolutely toward the market 
this is what we are doing now this is i think what will be decisive 
for the entire perestroika the future of perestroika 
we are having now a very crucial situation in which we would like 
to hope for your cooperation and for your understanding 
those who are with us at this time have a good prospect of 
cooperation in our great country in our great market because of its 
tremendous potential but those who just stand on the sidelines who 
do not want to risk who want to wait and see who dont want to 
risk their dollars well they will remain i think observers for 
years to come 
well make sure that that is so 
</TEXT>
