<TEXT>
the supreme court today asked the bush 
administration to offer its opinions about key limitations on free 
agency in the national football league 
the court asked justice department lawyers to comment on a lower 
courts ruling that nfl restrictions on a players switch to another 
team do not violate federal antitrust law 
the justices are not expected to say whether they will review 
that ruling until hearing from the government lawyers which could 
take months 
no further court action in the case is likely before october 
when the justices return from their summer recess scheduled for 
late june or early july 
the antitrust case is an outgrowth of a 24day strike in 1987 by 
the national football league players association the walkout ended 
without a new contract between the players and the leagues 28 team 
owners 
but the owners continued to enforce an expired contract signed 
in 1982 containing provisions that restrict free agency 
the provisions limit a players ability to negotiate and sign 
with a new team the players original team is given the right to 
match a competing clubs offer 
if the original team declines to match the offer the players 
new team must compensate the other team with draft choices 
the provisions are called the leagues first refusalcompensation 
system the nfl has a separate provision known as plan b in which 
teams protect 37 players and permit the rest to become free agents 
the players association filed a federal lawsuit in 1987 accusing 
the league and team owners of violating antitrust law by enforcing 
the first refusalcompensation system after the expiration of the 
1982 contract 
the owners said they are exempt from antitrust law arguing that 
the old collective bargaining agreement still is valid they said 
the players union is trying to win in court what it was unable to 
win at the bargaining table 
us district judge david doty of minneapolis in 1988 ruled in 
favor of the players ordering a trial to determine whether the 
owners were guilty of antitrust violations 
but the 8th us circuit court of appeals overturned dotys 
decision last november 
in a 21 ruling the appeals court said the league and owners 
were exempt from antitrust law because of the previously negoiated 
union contract 
the players choice now is between further negotiations or a 
strike the appeals court said permitting them to sue under such 
circumstances would upset the level playing field created by 
federal labor law it added 
in a dissenting opinion judge gerald w heaney said the appeals 
court ruling permits the owners to violate the antitrust law 
indefinitely 
the 8th circuit courts decision was hailed by the owners as a 
major victory that would spur the players to return to the 
bargaining table 
the players association responded by decertifying itself as the 
players bargaining agent a move designed to nullify the 1982 
contract and revive the antitrust suit 
nine current and former union officials substituted themselves 
for the association in filing the appeal acted on today 
they said the 8th circuit court ruling amounts to a virtually 
unlimited antitrust exemption for employers in unionized 
industries 
eight states supported the appeal saying their efforts to 
curtail anticompetitive behavior could be hampered by the appeals 
court ruling the states are new york arizona hawaii louisiana 
michigan texas utah and wyoming 
the case is powell vs nfl 891421 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900604-0101 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today used a dispute over 
haitian refugee rights to strengthen a federal law requiring the 
government to pay legal fees to winning opponents in lawsuits 
the court unanimously rejected bush administration arguments 
aimed at limiting the attorneys fees 
the justices said the government generally must reimburse winning 
opponents not only for the legal fees they incur in the main 
lawsuit but also for subsequent litigation over the size of those 
fees 
the haitian refugees sued the government in 1981 over its policy 
of locking up aliens caught while trying to enter the united states 
illegally 
until 1981 the government generally allowed the aliens to go 
free on parole pending hearings on their applications for admission 
to the country 
the haitians said they almost never were paroled before their 
applications were acted upon a process that can take longer than a 
year 
the refugees accused the government of discriminating against 
them because they are black and also said the immigration and 
naturalization service violated federal rules by summarily adopting 
harsher treatment for haitians than other aliens 
the refugees ultimately won an important though not total 
victory 
the did not win on the discrimination claim but the government 
conceded that the ins may not consider race or national origin in 
determining parole and adopted new rules on refugees 
federal courts that reviewed the case said there is no doubt that 
the haitians won their freedom because of the lawsuit and those 
refugees later returned to custody were detained under new fairer 
rules 
the government argued that the haitians did not win key elements 
of their lawsuit and should not be entitled to recover legal fees 
under the equal access to justice act 
the act generally requires reimbursement of legal fees for those 
who prevail in suits against the government 
a federal judge ruled against the government on the fees question 
in the haitian case and awarded more than 1 million to lawyers who 
represented the refugees 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals substantially upheld the 
judges decision and ordered further hearings to recompute the 
amount owed the lawyers 
the appeals court also said the government must reimburse the 
haitians lawyers for fees they incurred litigating the fees issue 
what the appeals court called the feesforfees issue 
the supreme court today agreed rejecting the governments 
argument that the feesforfees claim should be denied because 
the governments position in the fee litigation was substantially 
justified 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said that since 
the government lost the principle part of the case it is not 
entitled to relitigate the fees issue 
the case is commissioner of ins vs jean 89601 
</TEXT>
