<TEXT>
lawyers may withhold their state bar 
association dues if the association uses the money to campaign for 
political or social causes a unanimous supreme court ruled today 
the court said a california bar group violated the freespeech 
rights of 21 lawyers who did not want their dues spent to promote 
such causes as a nuclear weapons freeze and handgun control 
compulsory dues may not be expended to endorse or advance a gun 
control or nuclear weapons freeze ballot initiative chief 
justice william h rehnquist wrote for the court 
conversely he said the freespeech rights of lawyers are not 
violated when their dues are used to help discipline members of the 
bar or to propose ethical codes for the profession 
the justices overturned a california supreme court ruling last 
year that said the bar association was free to use the money for 
practically anything but financing campaigns of candidates for 
public office 
the california court said the bar association with power to help 
license and discipline lawyers is more like a state agency than a 
labor union 
the us supreme court previously has limited the power of unions 
to spend dues money for publicissue lobbying 
today rehnquist said the bar association is more like a union 
than a typical government agency noting the lawyers group is 
funded not by the taxpayers but by members dues 
also he said the bar association was formed primarily as an 
advisory organization lawyers are licensed or disciplined by the 
state supreme court with advice from the association 
the ruling buttresses decisions by courts outside of california 
that have limited the power of state bar associations to use 
members dues for ideological purposes 
the case is keller vs state bar of california 881905 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

