<TEXT>
when alexander p russo returned from his 
stint as a world war ii combat artist he couldnt bear to draw 
people he had seen too many soldiers riddled with gunfire too many 
mangled bodies 
i couldnt paint a figure for years said russo who 
witnessed the allied invasion of the normandy beaches on june 6 
1944 i wanted to do landscapes i was trying to get my mind back 
to a positive focus 
russo was one of eight artists in the navys combat art section 
which he joined after the dday invasion they lived with the 
troops and followed them into battle capturing the fighting on 
sketchpads and later on canvas 
i think good art or great art captures the sense of the 
situation in this case it was the essence of battle the horror of 
battle said russo a retired art professor from hood college in 
this western maryland city 
but russo who taught at the corcoran school of art in 
washington dc and chaired hoods art department for 15 years 
does not want to be known solely as a combat artist his 
contemporary art which bridges realism and abstraction is in 
collections and museums in the united states and europe 
im a functioning artist the war was just one phase he said 
last week it was an opportunity to be creative but it was just a 
beginning 
russo was 20 when he joined the navy in october 1942 after 
completing art studies at pratt institute in new york city as part 
of an amphibious intelligence unit he made shoreline drawings and 
plaster terrain models 
he sketched troops landing in sicily and fires raging in london 
after german bombing attacks 
russos firefighters in london at night is part of an 
exhibit at the washington navy yard in the nations capital the 
painting in brown black red and orange tones depicts firefighters 
dousing flames that dart from windows and roofs toward a dark sky 
fortyfour years ago wednesday russo landed with thousands of 
troops on the beaches of normandy i was moved by some things that 
the others were not subtle things like troops waiting or grave 
diggers pausing russo said 
in his work from normandy russo painted to the burial 
ground which shows soldiers tending to the dead on a hillside 
four soldiers rest from digging two carry a covered stretcher to a 
cemetery studded with crosses 
later as part of the combat art section russo spent months in 
washington developing his sketches into complete works the unit was 
founded by griffith baily coale who persuaded the navy to let 
artists accompany ships into action and record the battles in ways 
that photographers and journalists could not 
there was practically no color photography done during world 
war ii it was too bloody expensive said john d barnett curator 
of the navy art collection at the naval yard the color wasnt 
true so they figured they were better off with black and white 
russo completed 250 drawings sketches and paintings that are 
part of the navys historic record of the war 
it was the beginning of a search for deeper values that im 
still searching for and still trying to represent in my work he 
said 
</TEXT>
