wants to know why some people have perfect pitch and others cant 
carry a tune in a bucket 
it is talent or it is teachable asks dr louis s russo 
jr a member of the first coast pop orchestra 
hes looking for clues by studying a group of professional 
musicians and a group of people who have never had a music lesson 
as children we develop language and grammar skills by 
listening to our parents talk said russo why is it that people 
develop these music skills long before they go to school yet many 
people cant even hum a tune we all listen to music even though we 
all cant play it 
russo first tested eight righthanded musicians with the 
jacksonville symphony orchestra all were connected to a brain 
mapping device and monitored while reading a magazine article 
sightreading music singing a simple song from memory and while 
listening to bach piano music 
the brain maps showed when each musician read words the left 
part of the brain was activated research has shown language is 
processed by the left side of the brain the right side was 
activated when they sang or listened to music 
but when the musicians were asked to sight read a piece of music 
both sides of the brain began working 
so the right side of the brain is necessary in all musical 
functions but the left side is activated as the functions become 
more complex he said 
