spiraling health care costs labor and 
managements biggest sticking point in collective bargaining are 
forcing companies nationwide to take extraordinary steps such as 
setting up their own medical clinics or physician networks 
goodyear tire amp rubber co for instance has three medical 
clinics at plants in oklahoma ohio and alabama where workers can 
visit a physician eye doctor or pharmacist for 15 followup 
visits are 5 
there are two ways to go decrease benefits and jack up 
premiums for workers or find a better and cheaper way says 
consultant victor williams 
more than a dozen fortune 500 companies have called williams in 
the past year inquiring about goodyears experience in the medical 
business he said 
goodyear estimates it saves 1 million a year on its 163 million 
health care bill it just scratches the surface but it helps 
said spokesman bob mercer 
employees benefit as well said jr countryman of the united 
rubber workers which represents goodyear workers in alabama it 
sure has cut down on our costs he said 
but not all management efforts to trim health care costs are 
being embraced by workers 
in fact union workers nationwide increasingly find themselves 
trying to fend off management efforts to shift health care costs to 
workers the issue was at the heart of 78 percent of the strikes 
waged last year by unions according to one study 
most recently a twoyear battle to resolve health care costs in 
the railroad industry proved unsuccessful last month president 
bush was forced to appoint an emergency board to try and prevent a 
strike 
in that dispute the major railroads which for decades have 
provided workers with a solid lowcost health care package wanted 
the 235000 brakemen engineers and other workers who keep the 
nations freight system moving to pay higher deductibles and make 
payroll contributions 
then they have to think twice because its not something 
someone else is going to pay for 100 percent said charles 
hopkins chairman of the national railway labor conference which 
represents management in the dispute 
union officials contend shifting health care costs to workers 
does little to solve a greater problem that merits congress 
attention how to rein in runaway medical costs 
to try to pin the blame on some poor worker worried about their 
kid in the middle of the night is really outrageous said bob 
master of the communications workers of america which fought a 
health care battle for telephone workers in the northeast last year 
hopkins said management has no choice but to try to shift part of 
the burden to workers because we are being consumed by the cost of 
our socalled fringe benefits 
besides trying to shift premium costs to workers companies are 
also moving to restrict a workers right to choose a doctor some 
also are auditing patients bills 
many companies are now setting up preferred provider 
arrangements medical networks that provide services to workers at 
a negotiated price often employers provide financial incentives 
for workers to use the ppo rather than their own family doctor 
other companies such as florida power amp light are hiring nurses 
to visit hospitals to audit patients bills to make sure money isnt 
being wasted the effort said spokesman michael millhorn is an 
attempt to save money without hurting workers 
we dont want to mess with the level of benefits if we can 
avoid it millhorn said 
paul oneill chairman of alcoa the aluminum company of america 
told a house panel recently that he didnt feel comfortable 
intervening in workers medical care decisions 
oneill noted that employers do not have a say in what type of 
car or food a worker buys 
yet here i am in the middle of personal medical care he said 
union leaders who have long been pushing for some type of 
national health care system hope the problems will lead business to 
join them in supporting health care reform rather than merely 
trying to pass costs on to workers 
thats simply a blamethevictim strategy that may look good in 
the short term and for the balance sheet but what we should be 
saying is hey lets try to get a permanent solution to this 
problem said karen ignagni the aflcios expert on health care 
according to a study by the service employees international 
union workers outofpocket expenses for health care grew faster 
than wages from 1986 to 1989 
the biggest increase was in employee contributions to premiums 
for family health coverage which rose from 1430 to 2412 if 
current trends continue the study found health insurance premiums 
will consume 27 percent of takehome pay by 1998 
its a national problem and must be addressed nationally 
aflcio president lane kirkland said recently 
ignagni and other union leaders said government involvement is 
crucial because theres a limit to how creative labor and management 
can be at reducing health care costs for instance she said little 
can be done at the bargaining table to bring down the cost of a 900 
hospital room 
the lesson of the 90s is that there is a limit to what you can 
do to change the slope of the curve she said 
