the supreme court on monday barred connecticut 
officials from pressing drunkendriving charges against a man 
acquitted of manslaughter in a fatal traffic accident 
the court without comment let stand a ruling that the second 
prosecution would violate the motorists doublejeopardy 
constitutional rights 
the justices ruled in a similar case may 29 by a 54 vote they 
said a new york man who pleaded guilty to drunken driving and 
related traffic offenses in a fatal car crash may not be prosecuted 
later for homicide and assault 
in the case acted on monday john lonergan was driving a car in 
hartford on may 22 1985 when he collided with a motorcycle driven 
by scott sementilli 
sementilli died the next day from his injuries 
longeran was charged with manslaughter and driving while 
intoxicated and the state decided to try him only on the 
manslaughter count a judge ruled that the state had failed to prove 
beyond a reasonable doubt that lonergans alleged intoxication 
caused sementillis death and ordered lonergan acquitted 
state prosecutors then sought to try lonergan for driving under 
the influence of liquor but a judge threw out the prosecution that 
ruling was upheld by the connecticut supreme court last year 
the state court said retrying lonergan would violate the 
constitutions ban on multiple prosecutions for the same crime 
the record clearly indicates that in the second prosecution for 
operating while under the influence the state will rely on and seek 
to prove the same act of operating while intoxicated that was 
necessary to prove the manslaughter charge in the first 
prosecution the state court said 
the case is connecticut vs lonergan 891295 
