nelson mandela began a world tour 
monday to urge countries not to drop sanctions against south africa 
even though the countrys whitedominated government has abandoned 
some racist policies 
apartheid is still alive the african national congress 
leader told an overflow crowd of 25000 people who took the 
afternoon off to hear him speak in the gabarone national stadium 
mandelas 13nation sixweek trip which includes stops in the 
united states follows a tour last month by south african president 
fw de klerk 
during the trip de klerk said he expected european leaders to 
reduce or end some economic social and diplomatic sanctions against 
south africa in response to the reforms his government is carrying 
out 
but mandela whose anc is the main black group working to end 
white rule said to stop sanctions now would be a stab in the 
back 
also monday officials at the united nations said 
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar will send a team of senior 
un officials to south africa on saturday for 10 days to discuss 
ending apartheid 
the team will meet members of the south african government 
representatives of political parties movements and other 
organizations on the latest developments concerning apartheid a 
statement said 
mandela said he intends to give leaders in africa europe and 
north america the correct picture of what is happening in south 
africa he said that despite relaxation of restrictions on political 
activity and repeal of some apartheid laws the main issue of black 
voting rights and selfdetermination has not been addressed 
under apartheid the black majority has no vote 
while mandela is trying to persuade world leaders to keep up the 
pressure on the south african government de klerk is expected to be 
making dramatic changes at home 
the government has already announced that later this month it 
expects parliament to pass a bill repealing the separate amenities 
act which allows the segregation of public facilities such as 
parks libraries and restrooms 
sometime this week many observers and newspapers have predicted 
de klerk will either lift the 4yearold national state of emergency 
or repeal most of it ending the state of emergency has been one of 
the main conditions the african national congress has set as a 
prerequisite for the lifting of sanctions and for formal 
constitutional negotiations with the government 
if the state of emergency is lifted that will be a victory for 
us mandela told reporters as he boarded a 12seat twinengine 
botswana government plane in johannesburg 
we have been demanding the lifting of the state of emergency 
which has been identified by us as an obstacle to negotiations the 
lifting was part of the agreement reached during our may 24 talks 
with the government he said 
mandela told the gabarone rally that sanctions and the ancs 
armed struggle would end when fundamental and irreversible changes 
occur in south africa 
