<TEXT>
secretary of interior manual lujan and 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter agreed monday to improve 
recruitment and employment opportunities in their agencies for 
hispanic students 
lujan and yeutter signed separate memorandums of understanding 
with the hispanic association of colleges and universities to 
develop a hispanic serving institutions partners program within 
the two agencies 
the agreements are a first for hispanics the interior department 
already has special programs for blacks attending historically black 
land grant colleges 
we must take every step possible to ensure that the full 
potential of all americans is developed so that we can successfully 
meet the complex challenges of the 21st century lujan said 
association president antonio rigual noted that president bush 
has described the low educational attainment by hispanics a 
crisis 
i can tell you that the consequence of the hispanic education 
crisis will affect the entire nation said rigual if all of us 
the federal government the education associations the private 
sector and school systems dont begin immediately to pull together 
as a team on behalf of hispanic students and hispanic families to 
create some real remedies to the problems of hispanic education 
then we will all suffer 
the documents take effect immediately and require the agencies to 
provide job information workstudy programs and internships and to 
assist the association in developing relevant curricula conduct 
career fairs and other recruitment activities 
the memorandums also call for creation of a committee to advise 
the two federal agencies and the association on policies 
procedures programs and services to improve the scope and quality 
of educational programs for hispanics 
lujan said a minimum of 5 million will be spent over the 
fouryear life of the contract and all 10 interior bureaus will 
participate 
rigual said similar pacts also are in the works with the 
department of energy and labor 
the association founded in may 1986 in san antonio texas 
represents colleges and universities where hispanics constitute at 
least 25 percent of the total student enrollment the 113 
institutions located in 10 states and puerto rico enroll almost 
onehalf of all the hispanic college students in the united states 
</TEXT>
