<TEXT>
the supreme court assured police monday they 
may continue using jailhouse undercover agents ruling that such 
agents may trick suspects into confessing without first warning them 
of their rights 
by an 81 vote the justices said jailed criminal suspects need 
not receive socalled miranda warnings about their right to remain 
silent and get a lawyers help before being questioned by undercover 
agents 
in its famous 1966 ruling the court ruled that police must give 
such warnings before interrogating suspects who are in custody 
but writing for the court in an illinois case monday justice 
anthony m kennedy said miranda warnings are not required when 
the suspect is unaware that he is speaking to a law enforcement 
officer and gives a voluntary statement 
kennedy added 
conversations between suspects and undercover agents do not 
implicate the concerns underlying miranda the essential ingredients 
of a policedominated atmosphere and compulsion are not present when 
an incarcerated person speaks freely to someone that he believes to 
be a fellow inmate 
justice thurgood marshall the lone dissenter said the ruling 
may well result in a proliferation of departmental policies to 
encourage police officers to conduct interrogations of confined 
suspects through undercover agents 
the decisions impact is confined to jailed suspects not yet 
charged with the crime about which they are questioned the court in 
1980 ruled that law enforcement officials cannot hire jailhouse 
informants to elicit confessions from those already charged with a 
crime or those who have invoked their right to a lawyers help 
mondays ruling is a defeat for lloyd perkins who unwittingly 
made incriminating remarks about a murder to an undercover agent at 
a hillsboro ill jail 
perkins later was charged with fatally shooting richard 
stephenson on nov 8 1984 in fairview heights ill 
miranda was not meant to protect suspects from boasting about 
their criminal activities in front of persons whom they believe to 
be their cellmates kennedy wrote for the high court adding that 
perkins spoke at his own peril 
the decision reversed an illinois appeals court ruling that the 
statements perkins made to parisi could not be used as trial 
evidence 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

