<DOCNO> AP900604-0170 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
middleclass black women with college educations 
are twice as likely to bear lowbirthweight babies as whites of the 
same income and education a study found 
the study of more than 100000 births in chicago suggests that 
the effects of poverty linger for generations the researchers said 
monday 
low birth weight is the most important predictor of whether 
babies will die said the lead researcher dr james w collins jr 
who specializes in newborns at childrens memorial hospital 
the united states which ranks 22nd among developed countries in 
infant survival is losing its fight to reduce the infant mortality 
rate collins said 
he and a colleague dr richard j david of cook county hospital 
examined 103072 birth records about half of them for whites and 
half for blacks for the years 1982 and 1983 
they found that lowbirthweight babies those less than 5 
pounds were born to blacks at twice the rate they were to whites 
at virtually every income and educational level 
in households earning less than 10000 a year 15 percent of the 
black babies were of low birth weight compared with 8 percent for 
whites 
in households earning 30000 to 40000 a year the rate was 10 
percent for blacks and 5 percent for whites 
among mothers with less than a high school education the rate 
was 16 percent for blacks and 7 percent for whites and for mothers 
with a college ecucation the rate was 10 percent for blacks and 5 
percent for whites 
if youre middle class and black despite having education 
being of optimal age to have children and living in a 20000 to 
30000ayear household you still do twice as bad as whites 
similar to you collins said 
the study appears in the june issue of the american journal of 
public health where the two researchers write we suspect that 
the persistently high rate of low birth weight infants among blacks 
reflects generations of poverty 
the researchers added they also suspect that it may require 
more than one generation of nonpoverty and adequate services to see 
an impact upon infant birth weight 
the researchers didnt examine specific factors that might have 
caused the differences but collins said he believed nutrition 
during adolescence may be key 
i think psychosocial stress is also a factor but its very 
hard to measure said collins another may be that fewer blacks 
than whites seek prenatal care even when both can afford it he 
said 
he cited a study published in november 1988 about 31000 largely 
middleclass women in a california health maintenance organization 
it found that prenatal care could narrow the gap between rates of 
lowbirthweight babies between blacks and whites but that blacks 
sought such care less often 
i dont know how much racism comes into it collins said 
speculating that some blacks may have had so many bad experiences 
with medical institutions that they tend to avoid them 
dr kwangsun lee a university of chicago professor of 
pediatrics and obstetricsgynecology said he believed none of the 
factors that has been studied such as improved prenatal care 
reduced teenage pregnancy or improved nutrition would eliminate 
the discrepancies improvement in all those areas might help said 
lee who wasnt involved with the study 
the study which has not been clearly done is what is the effect 
of a stressful life situation he said when women in low social 
classes have repeated stressful events what happens to the womb has 
not been defined yet 
american indians have normalweight babies as often as whites 
even though they are poorer than whites or blacks lee said 
suggesting that none of the effects of poverty usually blamed for 
lowbirthweight babies appears to be affecting them 
lee and collins noted that british researchers showed as long as 
20 years ago that the rate of low birth weights didnt decline until 
the second generation after a woman attained more affluence 
it is more important how you are brought up than whether you 
marry a millionaire lee said 
</TEXT>
