<TEXT>
the vermont supreme court upheld a 
sixmonth state moratorium on civil jury trials such as divorces and 
said the budgetcutting measure didnt interfere with the right to a 
speedy trial 
the moratorium intended to save 75000 to help the state avoid 
a deficit did not affect criminal trials 
the constitutional guarantee of a speedy trial must be considered 
in context the court said adding that speedy need not be instant 
the ban only affected civil cases which usually involve 
divorces property disputes personal injury claims malpractice 
suits and breaches of contract it could be overriden in specific 
cases by the administrative trial judge 
the moratorium which will expire july 1 was imposed by the 
court in january as a way to cope with budget cuts prompted by the 
states sagging economy the court was ordered to reduce its budget 
by about 300000 
the 220member vermont trial lawyers association filed a 
classaction lawsuit seeking to overturn the ban it said that the 
federal and state constitutions guarantee the right to a speedy 
trial 
however the court said its action was constitutional and a 
prudent way to manage caseloads and resources 
our precedents do not support the absolutist view of the jury 
trial right that the petitioners espouse said the decision 
written by retired chief justice albert barney 
even with the moratorium barney noted most cases will come to 
trial faster than in past years 
the petitioners remedy of instant access to a jury cannot be 
found in the constitutional jury trial rights on which they rely 
caseloads cannot be managed on the simplistic position that everyone 
is entitled to an immediate trial whenever they are ready for one 
barney wrote 
the vermont supreme court decision is counter to a federal court 
ruling in california that held civil jury trials in us district 
court could not be suspended because of fiscal restraints 
but the vermont justices said the federal ruling centered around 
the length of the moratorium not the moratorium itself the 
justices said the vermont moratorium delayed civil jury trials for 
only a relatively short period of time 
the trial lawyers association had sought to disqualify the 
entire fivemember supreme court from the case arguing that the 
justices issued the moratorium and therefored had a conflict of 
interest 
the court disagreed but two members disqualified themselves 
because of personal relationships with some of the law firms 
involved in the challenge 
barney and another retired justice took their places on the court 
</TEXT>
