<TEXT>
the grain agreement signed by president bush 
and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev continues the principal trade 
between the two countries that is nowhere near its potential a food 
processing executive said monday 
we could be doing 250 billion a year in trade said george 
melnykovich president of the food processing machinery and supplies 
association 
bush and gorbachev signed a fiveyear agreement friday to 
increase the annual minimum shipments of us grain to the soviets 
to 10 million metric tons from 9 million tons recent shipments have 
greatly exceeded the minimums 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds about 367 bushels of wheat 
or 394 bushels of corn 
the current pact which has been in effect since 1983 expires 
dec 31 such grain agreements have existed since 1976 
the agreement is worth roughly 6 billion to 8 billion to 
farmers and exporters over the five years said agriculture 
department analyst cina radler its impossible to pinpoint the 
exact value because of fluctuations in market price she said 
take out the grain agreement and the rest of trade between the 
two countries in infinitesimal said melnykovich but he said the 
soviets want so much and the united states has so much to offer that 
trade should mushroom 
the main problem is money he said the soviet ruble is not worth 
much outside the soviet union so american companies dont want to 
be paid in soviet currency 
melnykovich predicted that in the next five years the soviet 
government would make the ruble a freely convertible currency that 
could be used in world trade 
melnykovich is one of the organizers of a threeday conference in 
washington that is bringing together 55 soviet ministers to discuss 
the state of the soviet food system and with us food companies 
its an unprecedented meeting between leaders of one us 
industry and top soviet officials said anthony jf oreilly 
chief ececutive officer of the hj heinz co and conference 
chairman 
