<TEXT>
turkish communists tried to legally 
register their party on monday despite a constitutional ban of 
marxist and religious parties 
two leaders of the united communist party nihat sargin and 
haydar kutlu registered the united communist party of turkey at the 
interior ministry 
the partys charter calls it a marxist revolutionary workers 
party based on class struggle the same words mentioned as a cause 
for banning in turkeys legal code 
the chief prosecutors office will now study the application 
which could make the party legal for the first time in 70 years 
sargin 64 a physician who is the party chairman and kutlu 36 
party secretarygeneral were released from prison a month ago they 
had been arrested in november 1987 upon their arrival from exile in 
west germany 
the two have been barred from foreign travel while their trial on 
attempting to stage a communist revolution in turkey continues 
sargin and kutlu told a news conference monday their aim was a 
turkey without fear exile or censorship and that the party will 
advocate human rights and ethnic rights for turkeys kurdish 
minority 
kurds are estimated to constitute 20 percent of the countrys 
total population of 56 million but are not recognized as an ethnic 
minority by the government 
the communist party was forced into exile in 1920 
for the past several years there has been a debate in turkey on 
whether the amend laws barring marxist and religious parties 
legalization of such parties is considered necessary for turkey 
to succeed in becoming a full member of the european economic 
community 
</TEXT>
