<TEXT>
the white house said monday president bush will 
nominate david h leroy former lieutenant governor of idaho as the 
negotiator charged with launching a new search for a palce to put 
the nations growing inventory of highly radioactive nuclear waste 
leroy 42 of boise idaho will canvass governors indian tribal 
leaders and others in hopes of uncovering a site willing to become a 
temporary or permanent highlevel nuclear waste repository 
in a telephone interview from his law offices leroy said the 
task could make him the most unpopular person in america 
but he called it an important mission that could help solve a 
problem fraught with moral political and scientific 
ramifications 
he promised to mount an aggressive effort to search the 
country and us territories for localities that may have an 
untapped interest in accepting a nuclear waste repository 
congress ordered the president to appoint an independent nuclear 
waste negotiator in 1987 at the same time it designated nevadas 
yucca mountain on a nuclear weapons testing range as the most likely 
site for a repository 
the 1987 legislation ordered the energy department to drop work 
on two other candidate sites in texas and washington state and to 
begin the expensive detailed subterranean geological investigation 
necessary to see if yucca mountain is suitable for an installation 
that must confine the waste for at least 10000 years 
underground research has not yet begun the state of nevada has 
refused to grant permits for it and the question is tied up in court 
leroy a republican who narrowly lost a bid to unseat democratc 
gov cecil andrus in 1986 said congress felt very strongly that 
an aggressive effort should be made to determine whether there were 
any locations with a technically sound repository site that might be 
willing to assume a larger role voluntarily 
if the search produces a willing taker leroy is also charged 
with recommending acceptable terms to congress the legislation gave 
the negotiator until 1991 to complete the search leroy said a 
quick start is essential 
if confirmed he will operate independently from the department 
of energy but will not be responsible to the department it is a 
parttime post and leroy said he will keep up his law practice in 
boise 
leroy was idahos attorney general from 1979 to 1983 and its 
lieutenant governor from 1983 to 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

