<TEXT>
the los angeles county board of supervisors 
violated the rights of hispanics in 1981 by drawing voting districts 
that keep them from getting elected a federal judge ruled monday 
us district judge david kenyon ruling in a voting rights case 
said the boards five members conspired to protect their 
incumbencies and that of their allies when they redrew the 
countys five voting districts in 1981 
in so doing kenyon said the supervisors violated the 1965 
federal voting rights act and the equal protection clause of the 
14th amendment to the constitution 
hispanics make up about 35 percent of the countys 87 million 
people no member of any minority group has been elected to the 
board since 1875 
the mexican american legal defense and educational fund and the 
american civil liberties union foundation of southern california 
expressed jubilation at the ruling and demanded the results of two 
elections set for tuesday be invalidated 
county counsel dewitt clinton was in budget hearings monday and 
unavailable for comment but fifth district supervisor mike 
antonovich who is not up for reelection said the ruling would be 
appealed 
maldef the civil liberties group and the us justice department 
had sued in 1988 accusing the supervisors of deliberately spreading 
the hispanic population across several districts to keep hispanics 
from getting elected 
this is truly a great and historic day said marc rosenbaum 
an attorney for the civil liberties group 
for 115 years the los angeles county board of supervisors has 
been an exclusive male allwhite club today that club membership 
is open to everyone 
in washington us attorney general dick thornburgh hailed the 
decision as a victory against discrimination in the most important 
role citizens play in our democracy the right to vote in free and 
fair elections in districts drawn without bias 
representatives of both sides said it wasnt immediately clear 
how the issue will be resolved 
maldef officials said they would demand the immediate creation of 
a largely hispanic district 
we want a remedy that encompasses a fair opportunity for our 
community to represent itself and to elect representatives who will 
represent its interests said antonia hernandez president and 
general counsel for maldef 
she and rosenbaum also said new elections should be held in the 
first and third supervisorial districts where voting takes place 
tuesday 
ed edelman who is seeking reelection in the third district 
declined comment on kenyons ruling 
in the first district retiring supervisor pete schabarum said he 
had not read kenyons decision i continue to believe however 
that district lines should not be based on ethnic factors he 
said and i find it incredulous that a 1981 plan can be overturned 
based on 1990 demographics 
in his ruling the judge concluded that hispanics and 
nonhispanics are widely polarized when it comes to voting 
hispanics vote in large numbers for fellow hispanics he said and 
nonhispanics rarely vote for hispanics 
given the estimated levels of polarization including the 
effects of nonhispanic bloc voting an hispanic candidate is unable 
to be elected to the board under the current configuration of 
supervisorial districts kenyon said 
