an agreement signed by the contras and the government on 
wednesday specifies contra representation in government ministries 
but the agreement to disarm at least 500 contras a day has not 
been met and even if it were half the contras would remain under 
arms by june 10 the day agreed to by the rebels following talks 
with the new government of violeta barrios de chamorro 
top contra leader israel galeano blamed the limited numbers of 
un peacekeeping troops and organization of american states 
officials who have been processing rebels who want to disarm for 
the slow pace of the demobilization 
but un peacekeeper lt col luis alejandre who is in charge of 
security zone six said many contras show up at the zone without 
their weapons and are turned back 
alejandre said the rebels had probably buried their weapons 
you can imagine the traffic in illegal weapons there would be 
if the un troops accepted rebels who did not hand over a weapon 
alejandre said 
he said that since sunday the contras have started turning in 
high quality weapons 
the ones before were all rusted out alejandre said 
galeano said the contras had left 7000 weapons behind in 
honduran camps before returning to nicaragua 
the four contra leaders who demobilized on monday were miguel 
angel sosa the contra army general staff inspector also known as 
commander emiliano enrique zelaya the medical chief of staff also 
known as commander henry or dr henry contra political advisor 
bernardo pastora and political advisor boanerge matus 
zelaya a medical doctor is to join the health ministry sosa 
and pastora are to go to the repatriation institute and matus is to 
join the agrarian reform institute 
of an estimated 13000 rebels only about 4000 have disarmed 
galeano said that although it was unlikely that the demobilization 
would be completed by june 10 we have embarked on an irreversible 
process 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

