<TEXT>
a dead gray whale was found to have plastic bags 
rubber gloves and other manmade refuse in its stomach but that 
probably didnt kill it an expert said monday 
months of lab tests may be needed to determine what killed the 
whale dubbed spot by animal lovers who tracked its movements through 
puget sound for about 10 weeks the 39foot whale was found dead 
wednesday near hartstene island in the sound about 35 miles 
southwest of seattle 
meanwhile monday the coast guard warned vessels to avoid two 
other dead whales spotted in the strait of juan de fuca 
pieces of wood bark plastic bags cloth rags and two rubber 
gloves were found in spots stomach during a necropsy sunday said 
john calambokidis of the cascadia research collective in olympia 
certainly nothing that we could see in that odd series of items 
would account for a death threat calambokidis said 
analysis of tissue samples taken from spots carcass over the 
weekend could take weeks to several months to complete according to 
a statement issued by cascadia and the marine animal resource center 
of seattle 
gretchen steiger a cascadia research biologist said spot seemed 
to be behaving normally and showed no sign of distress or injury 
before dying 
</TEXT>
