<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
may 29june 4 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the nations toughest newspaper recycling 
law has been approved in suffolk county on long island where all 
major papers will be required to use 40 percent recycled newsprint 
in their editions by the end of 1996 
the measure was approved may 29 by a 126 vote in the county 
legislature 
a group representing 64 daily papers in the state criticized the 
law 
any use of recycled paper should be market driven said john 
kutzer executive director of the new york newspaper publishers 
association we feel local government is perhaps going overboard 
with these requirements 
the law would apply to all daily and weekly newspapers printed 
sold or distributed in suffolk county provided their suffolk 
circulation is 20000 or more a week advertising circulars are 
included if they meet the circulation requirement 
the bill requires that newspapers be printed on stock containing 
at least 40 percent recycled paper by dec 31 1996 papers that do 
not comply would face a 500 fine each day 
the publisher of newsday the largest circulation daily on long 
island plans to challenge the law in court said spokesman sam 
ruinsky newsday says it uses 17 percent recycled paper for printing 
william k adler manager of corporate relations for the new york 
times cited a voluntary agreement approved by the publishers 
association in which they agreed to gradually increase the use of 
recycled paper that plan set a goal of 40 percent by the year 2000 
since the state has initiated a coordinated program attempts 
by individual counties to legislate their own timetables for 
recycled newsprint are counterproductive said adler 
the times is using 8 percent recycled fiber he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the florida supreme court ruled may 31 
that the sales tax paid on the purchase of magazines should also be 
applied to newspapers 
the court in a 60 opinion rejected an effort by magazine 
publishers to get the protection enjoyed by newspapers and went 
further deleting the newspaper exemption 
floridas statutory differentiation between magazines and 
newspapers for purposes of sales taxation burdens rights protected 
by the first amendment wrote chief justice raymond ehrlich 
william hyde an attorney who represented the florida press 
association said an appeal to the us supreme court is likely 
its making the acquisition of knowledge more difficult he said 
laura besvinick an attorney representing the miami herald said 
floridas largest newspaper was considering an appeal to the 
nations high court 
we think that a tax on the press impermissibly burdens the 
first amendment she said 
only magazines sold over the counter were taxed before 1987 when 
the state extended the sales tax to a variety of services and to the 
sale of newspapers 
the services tax was repealed in a political firestorm a few 
months later but the status quo was not reestablished newspapers 
regained their exemption while the tax was extended to the sale of 
all magazines 
the magazine publishers of america inc the hearst corp time 
inc golf digesttennis inc and others went to court to challenge 
the distinction 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the daily news blamed reduced advertising revenue 
may 29 in announcing the layoff of 17 machinists as it continued 
bargaining over expired contracts at the tabloid 
this is the beginning of the planned strategy of provoking the 
unions into strike action said theodore kheel adviser of the 
allied printing trades councils the 10 unions negotiating with the 
news 
no doubt there will be more of the same sort to come 
the news said laidoff workers would get between two and six 
weeks pay and three months medical coverage 
this was to be coupled with a group outplacement seminar for a 
total cost of 80000 the news said 
by terms of the existing agreements management is permitted to 
determine the manning level in this department said john t 
sloan the news vice president of human resources 
our decision couldnt be further delayed in light of slowing 
economic conditions in the new york advertising marketplace 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
communications workers at the associated press 
will vote on a tentative contract agreement that management called 
fair but union leaders said was inadequate 
the ap announced june 2 that it and local 1314 of the 
communication workers of america had reached a tentative agreement 
on a contract calling for a managed care approach to control the 
cost of the medical plan 
the agreement also calls for a 2350 weekly increase in 
topscale technician salaries in the first year and a 24 weekly 
boost in the second raising the topscale technician salary to 612 
in 1991 similar percentage increases were proposed for all other 
job classifications 
d byron yake aps director of human resources called the 
package fair and predicted it would be approved 
leaders of the cwa local agreed to submit the proposed contract 
to their 300 members for a vote but said they would recommend it be 
rejected 
jim peecook president of the union local said the health plan 
proposals represented a severe loss to those employees and their 
families he also said the proposed increase in pension benefits 
was inadequate 
terms of the present contract were extended until july 2 pending 
the vote the ap said 
</TEXT>
