<DOCNO> AP900604-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the miracle to hear eileen atkins describe it is 
that she succeeded as an actress at all 
its incredibly hard and i dont care what anybody says for 
people from my kind of background to get into the theater and become 
a classical actress says the british star of prin currently 
playing offbroadway at the manhattan theater club 
that background refers to the british workingclass atkinss 
father read gas meters her mother made dresses to both her 
parents acting meant entertainment in the most lowbrow sense not 
the meaty wideranging roles that have distinguished her career 
my mother wanted me to be a chorus girl because i tapdanced 
she recalls when i got to 12 and said im going to do 
shakespeare people thought i was crackers 
more than 40 years later the jokes on them a veteran of 
broadway and the west end last year she won londons equivalent of 
the tony award for her performances in shakespeares cymbeline 
and harold pinters mountain language at the royal national 
theater 
at 55 atkins belongs to that world class of british actresses 
that includes vanessa redgrave glenda jackson judi dench and 
maggie smith she shares with them a distinctively unglamorous 
british beauty face sharp and angular eyes suggesting inner 
strength and wisdom 
how did she reach the top sheer bloody obstinacy she says 
and a teacher named mr burton 
my mother sent me with a note to school saying i would do 
better if i spoke nicely as she put it atkins recalls 
the main drama teacher wanted 7 shillings and sixpence a week 
then about 250 to iron out young eileens cockney accent 
my mother said we cant afford it this man caught hold of 
me in the corridor and said ill teach you for nothing if you come 
whenever i tell you to and stay for as long as i want you to and 
theres no argument about anything she said 
atkins spent an hour after school with mr burton for the next 
five years and he first took her to the legitimate theater today 
her voice betrays no trace of her roots she has lost touch with 
burton and as far as she knows he has never come to see her on 
stage 
in prin by andrew davies atkins plays a lesbian 
headmistress of a womens teacher training college whose exacting 
idealism brings about her collapse 
sheila hancock won acclaim and an olivier award nomination for 
originating the role in the west end last winter but atkins plans a 
fresh approach i cannot bear playing something i have seen 
somebody do she says 
she says she has heard prin dismissed as a cross between 
the prime of miss jean brodie about an autocratic scottish 
teacher and the killing of sister george the play that broke 
the taboo on portraying lesbianism on the british stage 
but she remains fascinated by the title characters mixture of 
charisma and cruelty 
she only cares about standards about going for the 
truthsome people wont like her and some people will but im 
certainly not going to woo the audience to like me 
atkins hasnt acted in the united states since her harrowing 
performance as the schizophrenic mary barnes at the long wharf 
theater in new haven conn in 1980 
she has appeared four times on broadway starting with her 1966 
debut in the killing of sister george opposite beryl reid that 
role earned her a tony nomination for best actress as did her 
elizabeth i to claire blooms mary queen of scots in the 1972 
vivat vivat regina 
atkins has consciously eschewed stardom preferring british 
repertory to star vehicles and passing up the chance to act in 
upstairs downstairs the acclaimed television series that she 
and jean marsh cocreated 
she was the producers first choice for the part of sarah the 
maid which made a star out of pauline collins atkins doesnt 
regret it 
you get known as hudson or rose and then it takes you forever 
to get out of it again she says 
i would find it boring to play the same part continuously for a 
long time 
to me the interesting thing about work is finding the 
character and the rehearsal i like licking each part and once 
youve done that all you have left is learning it every week 
film roles have included vivid supporting performances in 
equus 1977 and the dresser 1983 but she lost a part in 
room with a view to her friend judi dench 
i didnt really think about the cinema when i was young 
because if you looked like me you werent a film star she says 
i was brought up to think i was extremely plain now i look 
back and say youre adorable 
her selfdeprecating manner drops only once when she gloats 
about finally getting a driving license 
its pretty good at 55 to learn to drive she says i think 
im prouder of that than anything 
</TEXT>
