<TEXT>
 
metamorphosen duetconcertino for clarinet amp bassoon prelude to 
capriccio op 85 by richard strauss cbs new stockholm chamber 
orchestra conducted by esapekka salonen paul meyer clarinet 
knut sonstevold bassoon 
strauss 18641949 wrote these works in the 1940s during the 
last decade of his life long gone were the years of his tremendous 
success as an opera composer his reputation as a master of 
everincreasing orchestation his fame as a conductor and even his 
decline in critical opinion into a composer of mere talent and no 
longer genius 
john cage was in his 30s arnold schoenberg was in his 60s and 
70s and music being composed at the time bore little resemblance to 
the early world of strauss who began writing music when the giants 
were brahms saintsaen dvorak tchaikovsky and bruckner 
in these last years strauss didnt change nor did the power of 
his music 
the metamorphosen are a distillation of his swirling lush 
romantic style the funeral march from beethovens eroica symphony 
appears throughout and at the end of the score strauss wrote in 
memoriam presumably for a destroyed germany 
salonen produces a sinewy subtle interpretation of this work of 
extraordinary richness and intensity he suddenly lifts out a brief 
line and puts it back in favor of another the dynamic range is 
broad though the recorded sound somewhat dry 
the duetconcertino is a rarely heard gem its sunny airy 
quality provides a nice contrast the soloists play freely and with 
an openness of character the prelude to capriccio strauss final 
opera serves as a nice reconciliation of the metamorphoses 
intensity and the duets lightness we are back to the style of der 
rosenkavalier a clear reminder of a different world 
by daniel wakin associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
songs for drella sire lou reed and john cale 
 
lou reed and john cales songs for drella is the rare rock 
performance that would sound more appropriate in a drawing room or 
theater than on an album 
the two former members of the velvet underground were 
commissioned to honor andy warhol their artistic coconspirator in 
the 1960s they returned with a 15song tribute that is part 
brilliant part aggravating and always compelling 
its a tribute without tears like theater it works far better 
as a single musical piece to be experienced in one sitting than on a 
disc that can be returned to frequently 
songs for drella loosely chronicles warhols life and the 
artists influence on the velvets from the explosive creativity in 
the 1960s to the disillusionment of warhols final years enough 
artistic license is taken for reed and cale to label the work a 
fiction 
the best moments are the two reed songs that bookend the disc 
small town describes an artists young life in a town he yearned 
to escape the album closes with reed figuratively standing over 
warhols grave he admits to resentments that can never be 
unmade but expresses the universal wish hed talked more with his 
friend while he was still alive 
musically the limited palette used by reed and cale does not 
invite repeated listenings the instrumentation is essentially 
guitar and keyboard with a few added colorings neither red nor 
cale is a strong or expressive singer and their deliveries are 
sometimes deadening 
one consumer note with records dying heres a good example of 
the type of creative cd packaging that could stop any pining for 
album covers its a handsome grouping of words and pictures with 
sharp black packaging the cd itself is set apart as a fluorescent 
portrait of warhol it looks terrific 
by david bauder associated press writer 
</TEXT>
