<TEXT>
forget all those highflown comments about the 
joys of directing movies now hear plaintalking bob hoskins its 
like being pecked to death by a thousand pigeons 
the london actor makes his directorial bow with the raggedy 
rawney which drew mixed reviews in new york and now is being 
released slowly across the country 
it wasnt my idea says hoskins i was in australia and 
the producer bob weis was talking about ideas for films i told 
him the old gypsy legend i think from the 100 years war i told him 
the story and said this would make a good film 
he leapt up in the air and said right give me a script 
youll direct it well do it in czechoslovakia i said oh will 
we it all came about through nepotism hes a close friend of 
mine and the crew was all family close friends 
hoskins and nicole de wilde wrote the script concerning a young 
soldier who deserts in wartime and joins a band of gypsies 
disguising himself as a rawney a gypsy term for a halfwit with 
unusual powers george harrisons handmade films provided the 5 
million budget and hoskins and crew went off to czechoslovakia for 
the filming 
hoskins who had done some directing in the theater was not 
fazed by the tight budget you can film an epic if you can figure 
out a way of doing it he reasoned for instance he staged a 
horse race in a small yard by carefully selecting camera angles 
concerning his pecked to death comment everybodys got 
questions for you they follow you into the loo toilet theyre 
banging on the door what pair of shoes dya want i dunno wear 
the shoes that fit ya 
theres no break at all the minute you get up questions they 
go on all the time some cant do their job until theyve had an 
answer from you 
he partly solved the problem when the cast presented him with a 
hat that was marked actor on one side and director on the 
other when i wore the actor side the crew wasnt allowed to 
ask me questions said hoskins who plays the leader of the gypsy 
band 
the raggedy rawney was filmed before the velvet 
revolution toppled communist rule hoskins and the rest of the 
company came to admire the czechs who worked on the film but they 
recognized certain barriers 
my translator was a wonderful guy who translated into czech 
three words behind me said hoskins sometimes i would go on 
about the regime and he said to me bob dont say those things in 
front of me im supposed to report you and if i dont theyre 
going to report me so we figured out that every time i wanted to 
say something id scratch my head and wed go for a walk 
one factor helped hoskins survive the hard days of filming 
great beer there wonderful beer i asked the guy who picked the 
locations how come theres always a really good bar near these 
places and there was great beer thats where the original 
budweiser comes from 
bob hoskins was born in suffolk on oct 16 1942 and his parents 
moved to london two weeks later just in time for a german bombing 
his life has been somewhat rambunctious ever since he quit school 
at 15 wandered from job to job until he happened into an acting 
audition by mistake he won a lead role and he hasnt stopped 
working 
while his fellow actors boast of training at drama academies 
hoskins says i actually learned from watching women i never had 
a class or was taught to act what i realized was that women have 
had to keep their mouths shut for thousands of years but they can 
express themselves very clearly without saying a word 
but a guy always hides what drama is is about the private 
moment its very difficult for a man to show the private moment 
its got nothing to do with femininity its a language i wouldnt 
say a body language its just a language telepathy maybe 
hoskins has had a busy schedule he has finished mermaids 
with cher and a thriller shattered and next plays a detective 
in plastic nightmare with tom berenger most of his work has 
been in this country but he declines to change his london base 
i couldnt take the kids away from their grandparents 
he commented ruefully that his wife dislikes his many absences 
and his kids rosa 6 and jack 4 are beginning to call me 
uncle 
though nominated for an academy award for his work in mona 
lisa hoskins most successful film has been the blockbusting 
who framed roger rabbit 
will he be around for a sequel 
i dont think they disney will make one it was wonderful an 
experience i wouldnt miss for the world but to do it again by the 
time we finished everyone was on their knees oh that was tough 
