<TEXT>
the toshiba machine co admits it doesnt know what 
happened to a shipment of hightech equipment that is reported to 
have gone to china in 1985 in violation of bans on sales of such 
machinery to communist countries 
three years later toshiba machine was penalized by the united 
states and japan for exporting sensitive machinery to the soviet 
union despite an agreement by western countries prohibiting such 
shipments to communist nations 
japan got a black eye for its trading practices from which it 
has still not recovered though regulations have been tightened 
the revelation of the china deal appears likely to raise the 
question of whether other hightech transactions slipped through in 
the years of less stringent supervision 
tracing such deals a halfdecade later can lead to dead ends as 
an associated press investigation showed in following up a report in 
a japanese magazine that machinery used in manufacturing computer 
memory chips had gone to china via hong kong 
the hong kong buyers have vanished now and there is no factory 
at least now in the building where the equipment was sent 
toshiba machines earlier problem came from exporting via 
norway sophisticated milling equipment in 1984 it allegedly 
permitted the soviet union to make submarines quieter and more 
difficult to detect and washington was furious when the story 
emerged in 1987 
in 1988 washington barred the parent company the electronics 
giant toshiba corp which holds 50 percent of toshiba machine from 
bidding on us government contracts for one year and toshiba 
machine was banned from exporting anything to the united states for 
three years japan blocked toshiba machine indefinitely from exports 
to communist countries 
the possible diversion of equipment to china is coming to light 
two years after the expiration of japans statute of limitations for 
violations of export law 
on may 19 the new monthly generalinterest magazine foresight 
published by shinchosha a major book and magazine publisher 
reported that toshiba machines electron beam lithography system 
went to china via hong kong in 1985 the system is able to 
manufacture vital parts for the mass production of memory chips and 
at the time it was prohibited for sale to china under japans export 
regulations 
the ap obtained copies of documents showing the price paid 
acceptance by the hong kong company and a receipt by the shanghai 
metal research institute dated sept 11 1985 for the eb105 rb40 
system 
toshiba machine officials confirmed the authenticity of the 
documents with the exception of the purported receipt by the 
shanghai metal research institute which was issued to the name of a 
chinese individual as seller 
all we can say is we sold the device to a hong kong company 
under proper procedures but we have no way of knowing what happened 
to it afterwards kinji matsumoto a director of toshiba machine 
told the ap 
matsumoto and other company officials said two men had tried to 
blackmail the company over the transaction last year the company 
refused to pay and reported the entire incident to the ministry of 
international trade and industry in may 1989 matsumoto said 
in march this year the ministrys export division requested a 
full explanation he said 
the ministry appeared satisfied with our explanation though 
its officials were not happy to hear about such an incident he 
said we were told we have to be more careful 
a ministry of international trade and industry official 
