<TEXT>
to finance their businesses women fish dealers 
in ghana had to pay 100 percent interest to moneylenders until 
womens world banking opened an office in accra and backed loans to 
them from a local bank 
the new yorkbased group since 1980 has been providing financial 
support and guidance in lessdeveloped nations for women who may 
have good business ideas but lack capital management skills and 
confidence 
the nonprofit organizations goals are equality for women in 
economic development as well as helping women achieve dignity from 
financial independence 
michaela walsh a former wall street investment banker who helped 
found wwb said banks in many countries traditionally have had 
little interest in small loans bankers may object to having to 
perform too much paperwork for too little profit or believe that a 
lack of confidence by a loan applicant indicates theyre a bad risk 
besides guaranteeing loans wwb trains women to run their 
businesses and publishes a trade atlas with profiles of 38 
countries explanations of transactions and a glossary of trade 
terms 
since it backed its first small loan for a bicycle repair shop in 
cali colombia in 1981 wwb has handled 12 million in loans some 
45000 loans averaging from 500 to 1500 through 46 affiliates 
in 35 countries in asia the americas europe and africa 
each affiliate is run by people from the country it serves in 
the ghanian capital of accra for example the affiliate was founded 
by an appeals court judge an economist and several manufacturers 
part of the work is convincing local banks to make the small 
loans to women who are poor and often illiterate wwb guarantees 
half the loan the local affiliate guarantees 25 percent and the 
local bank assumes 25 percent the borrower pays interest at the 
going market rate 
wwbs repayment rate has been 99 percent better than for most 
banks that lend in developing countries ms walsh said 
in some cases the affiliates act as advocates for women within 
their own families officers will talk to a man who controls the 
familys capital said christine hayanga a nairobi lawyer and 
regional officer for wwb in africa during a recent visit in new 
york 
we tell them we dont want you to die of a heart attack 
share some of your responsibility with your wife 
if the woman has no male relative with money to fund her business 
proposal wwb will guide her through the borrowing process 
one of the major things that attracted me to this was 
discovering in 1975 that women in most countries didnt even have 
credit ms walsh said she said banks generally did not want to 
deal with women because they lacked credit history collateral or 
legal standing 
ms walsh said she learned about the credit problem in 1975 at 
the united nations international womens conference in mexico city 
she also found that women worldwide accounted for 10 percent of 
income but owned less than 1 percent of assets the answer to 
changing the imbalance she thought was entrepreneurship 
at the same time she was inspired by the work of ela bhatt in 
india a member of indias planning commission who helped start a 
cooperative bank for poor women in india in 1974 
the wwb capital fund was built up by investors and support from 
the governments of canada sweden norway the netherlands and the 
united states as well as some corporations and foundations and the 
united nations 
wwb expects to branch out soon with larger loans through a new 
venture fund with limited partners making direct investments of up 
to 1 million 
wwb also is growing through new affiliates that include akron and 
yellow springs ohio philadelphia and charleston wva 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

