<DOCNO> AP900604-0278 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
states sometimes may be forced to pay refunds 
on money collected under taxes later ruled unlawful the supreme 
court said monday 
the court unanimously ruled in a florida case that states are not 
immune from being sued for refunds on unlawfully paid taxes and 
that the states can be ordered to provide some remedy 
but by a 54 vote in a case from arkansas the justices said 
businesses are not entitled to refunds on money paid under such 
unlawful taxes if state officials had no way of knowing the taxes 
interfered unconstitutionally with interstate commerce 
and the court said in the florida case that refunds are just one 
option in a panoply of remedies states may provide if successfully 
sued over taxes 
the court also stopped short of allowing full retroactivity for 
court decisions striking down state taxes instead it said refunds 
are possible if taxed activity occurred after the tax was 
invalidated or after state officials should have suspected the tax 
was flawed 
the justices were told that a highwayuse tax at issue in the 
arkansas case also is a controversy in pennsylvania kentucky new 
jersey and vermont with potential refunds of at least 630 million 
at stake 
but for other controversies the effect of mondays decisions is 
unclear 
for example the justices last year struck down a michigan law 
that taxed the pension benefits of retired federal employees but not 
the pensions of retired people who had worked for the state or its 
local governments 
the court said states must tax all government pensions or none 
but its decision left unanswered whether states must refund to 
pensioners the taxes already collected 
lawsuits seeking refunds have been filled in about half the 
states and the potential refund liability is about 2 billion 
the arkansas case decided monday was one of several in which the 
american trucking associations challenged the validity of a state 
highwayuse tax the associations sued arkansas in 1983 attacking 
the states highway use equalization tax 
a flat tax it resulted in a higher cost per mile for 
outofstate truckers than for instate truckers 
the arkansas supreme court upheld the tax but in 1987 the 
nations highest court struck down as unconstitutional two very 
similar taxes imposed on truckers by pennsylvania the arkansas 
legislature then repealed its state highwayuse tax 
the state supreme court however ruled that the trucking 
associations members were entitled to refunds only of the 49 
million in taxes paid into a special escrow account created in 1987 
about 160 million in flatuse taxes had been collected by 
arkansas before the escrow account was established in the wake of 
the supreme court decision on the pennsylvania taxes 
led by justice sandra day oconnor the court monday made clear 
that its 1987 ruling in the pennsylvania case was intended to 
apply only prospectively 
flat highway taxation was permissible for highway use that 
occurred before the date of our decision but not after oconnor 
wrote in the courts main opinion 
she was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and justices 
byron r white and anthony m kennedy justice antonin scalia joined 
in the result but for differing reasons 
justices john paul stevens william j brennan thurgood marshall 
and harry a blackmun dissented voting to impose greater 
retroactive liability on the states 
the court sent the case back to the arkansas supreme court for 
further study 
we are not in a position to determine precisely the nature and 
extent of the relief to which the truckers are entitled for their 
19871988 hue tax payments oconnor said that determination 
lies with the state courts in the first instance 
in the florida case the states tax structure at one time 
granted preferential treatment to alcoholic beverages made and 
bottled in florida from crops grown there 
the state legislature responding to a 1984 supreme court 
decision that struck down a similar tax setup in hawaii amended the 
law so that it granted preferences only for alcoholic beverages made 
from among other things citrus fruits 
the florida supreme court struck down the amended tax preference 
as unconstitutionally discriminatory against outofstate 
businesses but the state court ruled that distributors who had paid 
higher taxes were not entitled to any refunds 
the justices monday reversed the state supreme court ruling and 
sent the case back for a determination of what relief is required 
the state is free to choose which form of relief it will 
provide so long as that relief satisfies the minimum federal 
requirements he added 
the cases are mckesson corp vs division of alcoholic beverages 
and tobacco 88192 and american trucking association vs smith 
88325 
</TEXT>
