<TEXT>
president bush is expected to postpone new oil 
drilling off the california and florida coasts for up to 12 years 
in some areas so additional environmentalimpact studies can be 
done administration officials said monday 
the officials said the president appeared ready to endorse a 
course that would ban new exploration off florida until 2002 off 
northern california until 1997 and off southern california until at 
least 1992 
although the sources speaking on the condition of anonymity 
cautioned that bush still could change course and allow some 
leasing one official closely involved with the decision said i 
would be surprised if he did not go forward with the overall delay 
an electionyear decision to delay the leasing would play well 
among republicans in california and florida many have urged the 
delay voicing concerns about a negative reaction from voters if 
bush opened any areas to new drilling before the november balloting 
environmentalists have argued that the threat to the environment 
off both states has been shown and that new drilling should be 
banned altogether 
we will be very disappointed if all were offered by bush is 
a delay said lisa speer an attorney for the natural resources 
defense council the public has moved far beyond where delays are 
going to satisfy people its time to move to protect some of these 
areas permanently 
the longpending presidential decision was anticipated in the 
next few days 
while bush still had a range of options before him the consensus 
among officials who have worked on the decision is that bush will 
approve a delay in leasing for all three areas according to the 
administration sources 
postponing new drilling would conform to conclusions of a task 
force bush appointed last year to study the problem 
oil activity would be banned in all the areas until at least 
1992 when the interior department is to produce its next fiveyear 
plan for oil leasing around the country if bush keeps to the 
decision his aides expect the fiveyear plan includes a broad 
outline of what areas will be considered for leasing and how the 
department will deal with leases for those five years 
the president still had before him a variety of options ranging 
from opening the coasts to new offshore oil activity to imposing a 
moratorium 
the options that the president has expressed most interest in 
involve postponing any new drilling with the possibility of 
differing delay times the officials said 
they cautioned however that bush a former texas oil executive 
could switch courses at the last minute and back an option that 
would permit some new leasing activity 
bush named a task force last year headed by interior secretary 
manuel lujan to work with the national academy of sciences in 
studying the environmental impact of opening the three areas to oil 
leasing off northern southern california and the florida keys 
the task force in its report to bush in january cited a need 
for further study on the environmental and socioeconomic 
ramifications of new lease sales sources have said 
the broadest set of options initially placed before the president 
by his staff ranged from allowing immediate drilling in the study 
areas to permanently barring oil companies from the regions 
environmentalists have long opposed oil drilling in the three 
regions a 67million acre section of ocean off southern 
california 12 million acres 
off northern california and 13 million acres in the gulf of 
mexico near the florida everglades 
the environmentalists concerns about damage to beaches and 
endangering of wildlife from leaks intensified after the exxon 
valdez tanker spill off alaska a year ago 
the florida congressional delegation unanimously asked bush to 
bar new drilling off their state republican gov bob martinez who 
faces uncertain reelection prospects this year is a strong 
moratorium proponent 
in california the political positions are a bit more mixed but 
even conservative republicans now call for protection of 
environmentally sensitive areas from oil drilling 
republican sen pete wilson rcalif who faces only token 
opposition in the gop primary tuesday but a bruising campaign for 
governor of california is a strong moratorium backer who bucked the 
reagan administrations efforts to open new leasing areas off the 
states coast 
the policy initiated by thenpresident reagans interior 
secretary james watt opened to drilling the entire 14 
billionacre outer continental shelf but leasing has been blocked 
over the years by congressionally imposed moratoriums 
in florida the government sold 73 leases in the affected area in 
the early 1980s for 108 million the cost of buying the leases back 
could be closer to 200 million according to some interior 
department officials 
southern california is the only region of the country other than 
the gulf of mexico where offshore oil development is underway 22 
oil platforms are operating the current fiveyear lease program had 
anticipated additional lease sales last september but those sales 
were put off pending the presidents decision 
the northern california leases some 90 miles north of san 
francisco and off eureka had been scheduled for sale early last 
year but the sale was postponed 
